Creating an admin dashboard for your website involves setting up a web application that allows you to manage your site's content and settings. Below is a basic example using Flask, a lightweight web framework for Python. This example will guide you through setting up a simple admin dashboard with a main page.

### Prerequisites

1. **Python**: Ensure Python is installed on your system.
2. **Flask**: Install Flask using pip:
   ```bash
   pip install Flask
   ```

### Project Structure

Create a project directory and set up the following structure:

```
admin_dashboard/
│
├── app.py
├── templates/
│   └── index.html
└── static/
    └── style.css
```

### `app.py`

This is the main application file where you set up your Flask app and routes.

```python
from flask import Flask, render_template

app = Flask(__name__)

@app.route('/')
def index():
    return render_template('index.html')

if __name__ == '__main__':
    app.run(debug=True)
```

### `templates/index.html`

This is the HTML template for the main page of your admin dashboard.

```html
<!DOCTYPE html>
<html lang="en">
<head>
    <meta charset="UTF-8">
    <meta name="viewport" content="width=device-width, initial-scale=1.0">
    <title>Admin Dashboard</title>
    <link rel="stylesheet" href="{{ url_for('static', filename='style.css') }}">
</head>
<body>
    <div class="container">
        <header>
            <h1>Admin Dashboard</h1>
        </header>
        <nav>
            <ul>
                <li><a href="#">Dashboard</a></li>
                <li><a href="#">Users</a></li>
                <li><a href="#">Settings</a></li>
                <li><a href="#">Logout</a></li>
            </ul>
        </nav>
        <main>
            <h2>Welcome to the Admin Dashboard</h2>
            <p>Manage your website from here.</p>
        </main>
    </div>
</body>
</html>
```

### `static/style.css`

Add some basic styling for your dashboard.

```css
body {
    font-family: Arial, sans-serif;
    margin: 0;
    padding: 0;
    background-color: #f4f4f9;
}

.container {
    width: 80%;
    margin: 0 auto;
    padding: 20px;
}

header {
    background-color: #333;
    color: #fff;
    padding: 10px 0;
    text-align: center;
}

nav ul {
    list-style-type: none;
    padding: 0;
    background-color: #444;
}

nav ul li {
    display: inline;
    margin-right: 10px;
}

nav ul li a {
    color: #fff;
    text-decoration: none;
    padding: 5px 10px;
}

nav ul li a:hover {
    background-color: #555;
}

main {
    margin-top: 20px;
}
```

### Running the Application

1. Open a terminal and navigate to your project directory.
2. Run the Flask application:
   ```bash
   python app.py
   ```
3. Open a web browser and go to `http://127.0.0.1:5000/` to see your admin dashboard.

### Next Steps

- **Authentication**: Implement user authentication to secure your dashboard.
- **Database Integration**: Use a database to store and manage data.
- **Additional Pages**: Add more pages and functionality as needed.

This setup provides a basic starting point for an admin dashboard. You can expand it with more features and styles according to your needs.

